<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="88" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1420,1879]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1420,1446]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The expanded tip of the gonopod is bluntly rounded and the solenomere is comparatively long (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1633,1657]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1436,181,1609]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Bidentogon expansus Shelley 7. Collum and first ring, dorsal view 8. Midbody ring, dorsal view. 9, Epiproct, dorsal view. 10. Gonopods in situ, ventral view. 11. Right leg 3, ventral view. 12. Part of right gonopod, ventral view.Abbreviations: ac, acropodite; f3, femur of third leg; pf, prefemorite; sm, solenomere; tz, terminal zone. SEM stub WS33-7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4804921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4804921/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Figs 10, 12</figureCitation>
). There are 18 setae in the anterior marginal row on the collum (
<figureCitation box="[903,972,1456,1483]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1633,1657]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1436,181,1609]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Bidentogon expansus Shelley 7. Collum and first ring, dorsal view 8. Midbody ring, dorsal view. 9, Epiproct, dorsal view. 10. Gonopods in situ, ventral view. 11. Right leg 3, ventral view. 12. Part of right gonopod, ventral view.Abbreviations: ac, acropodite; f3, femur of third leg; pf, prefemorite; sm, solenomere; tz, terminal zone. SEM stub WS33-7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4804921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4804921/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1420,1879]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
<bibRefCitation author="Shelley, R. M." box="[199,366,1492,1519]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref20733" refString="Shelley, R. M. (2003) A new polydesmid genus and two new species from Oregon and Washington, U. S. A., with a review of Bidentogon Buckett &amp; Gardner, 1968, and a summary of the family in western North America (Polydesmida: Polydesmidae). Zootaxa, 296, 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 296.1.1" type="journal article" year="2003">Shelley (2003)</bibRefCitation>
provided the new name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shelley" authorityYear="2003" box="[646,781,1493,1518]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="expansus">
<emphasis box="[646,781,1493,1518]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">B. expansus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for Shear’s concept of 
<emphasis box="[1047,1221,1492,1518]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Shear" authorityYear="1972" box="[1047,1216,1492,1518]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">B. californicus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
He argued that the 
<typeStatus box="[151,210,1529,1555]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Shear" authorityYear="1972" box="[246,380,1528,1554]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis box="[246,380,1528,1554]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
had been mislabelled, since “Chamberlin’s clear intent, as evidenced by the published account, was to apply this name to the form at Stanford, the designated 
<typeStatus box="[851,899,1565,1591]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<bibRefCitation author="Shelley, R. M." box="[1005,1156,1564,1591]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref20733" refString="Shelley, R. M. (2003) A new polydesmid genus and two new species from Oregon and Washington, U. S. A., with a review of Bidentogon Buckett &amp; Gardner, 1968, and a summary of the family in western North America (Polydesmida: Polydesmidae). Zootaxa, 296, 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 296.1.1" type="journal article" year="2003">Shelley 2003</bibRefCitation>
, p. 10).” Thus, the specimens from Sacramento, on which Shear based his thinking, had probably been somehow mislabelled as the 
<typeStatus box="[1348,1407,1601,1627]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">types</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[151,293,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Shear" authorityYear="1972" box="[151,288,1636,1662]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">californicus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Further evidence that this was correct came from the many records of the real 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Shear" authorityYear="1972" box="[1184,1318,1636,1662]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1318,1636,1662]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">californicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from near the 
<collectingRegion box="[192,306,1672,1698]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">California</collectingRegion>
coast, as opposed to the inland Central Valley around Sacramento.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1420,1879]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
Here we supplement the original description and illustrations with new SEM pictures (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1325,1708,1735]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1633,1657]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1436,181,1609]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Bidentogon expansus Shelley 7. Collum and first ring, dorsal view 8. Midbody ring, dorsal view. 9, Epiproct, dorsal view. 10. Gonopods in situ, ventral view. 11. Right leg 3, ventral view. 12. Part of right gonopod, ventral view.Abbreviations: ac, acropodite; f3, femur of third leg; pf, prefemorite; sm, solenomere; tz, terminal zone. SEM stub WS33-7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4804921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4804921/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Figs 7–12</figureCitation>
). The expanded tip of the terminal zone (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[515,537,1745,1771]" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">tz</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[551,631,1744,1771]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–12" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1633,1657]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,181,1607]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1436,181,1609]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 7–12. Bidentogon expansus Shelley 7. Collum and first ring, dorsal view 8. Midbody ring, dorsal view. 9, Epiproct, dorsal view. 10. Gonopods in situ, ventral view. 11. Right leg 3, ventral view. 12. Part of right gonopod, ventral view.Abbreviations: ac, acropodite; f3, femur of third leg; pf, prefemorite; sm, solenomere; tz, terminal zone. SEM stub WS33-7." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4804921" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4804921/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) differentiates this species from 
<emphasis box="[996,1168,1744,1770]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="88">
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Shear" authorityYear="1972" box="[996,1164,1744,1770]" class="Diplopoda" family="Polydesmidae" genus="Bidentogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="7" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="californicus">B. californicus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
otherwise they are very similar.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
